    Digging into Fracking

    You’ve heard people talk about it: “Fracking.” And a lot of different things are being said.

    Get your questions answered; take this quiz to learn more about fracking for oil and natural gas.

    Start

    1 of 6

    1 of 6

    .

    Fracking seems pretty new. When was it first used?

    1880s
    1940s
    1980s

    1 of 6

    That's correct!

    That's incorrect!

    The first fracking job was completed in Grant County, Kansas in 1947. The first commercial hydraulic fracturing process – essentially the same technology used today – began in 1949. Over the last decade, hydraulic fracturing paired with horizontal drilling has inspired America’s shale revolution.

    Next

    Hotspot
    Hydraulic fracturing has produced more than 7 billion barrels of oil and 600 trillion cubic feet of natural gas since the 1940s.
    Hotspot
    Fracking has been in practice for more than 65 years and has been used in at least 2 million wells in the United States alone.
    Hydraulic fracturing has produced more than 7 billion barrels of oil and 600 trillion cubic feet of natural gas since the 1940s.
    Fracking has been in practice for more than 65 years and has been used in at least 2 million wells in the United States alone.

    That's incorrect!

    3 of 6

    .

    Fracking has helped create a lot of new jobs, how many of those are outside of the energy industry?

    Around 500K
    Less than 1MM
    More than 1.5MM

    3 of 6

    That's correct!

    That's incorrect!

    According to an IHS report, 1.6 million jobs are indirectly supported outside the industry – through purchases in the supply chain and labor income re-spent throughout the economy.

    Hotspot
    Fracking is projected to create 3.5 million jobs by 2035.
    Hotspot
    Shale development was responsible for $74 billion in government tax revenues in 2012, and it is estimated that it will generate $138 billion in government revenues by 2025.
    Fracking is projected to create 3.5 million jobs by 2035.
    Shale development was responsible for $74 billion in government tax revenues in 2012, and it is estimated that it will generate $138 billion in government revenues by 2025.

    4 of 6

    4 of 6

    .

    All of the water used in the fracking process is lost underground or otherwise wasted.

    True
    False

    4 of 6

    That's correct!

    That's incorrect!

    For example, 90 percent of the more than 14 million barrels of produced fluids from fracturing was reused in the first half of 2013 in the Marcellus shale play.

    Next

    Hotspot
    Shale wells require a large investment of water in the first three months, but most wells produce energy for decades without additional water investment.
    Hotspot
    Research advancements make it possible to use different types of water including produced water from other wells, saline groundwater, or even wastewater from other industries, cities, and households (“grey water”).
    Shale wells require a large investment of water in the first three months, but most wells produce energy for decades without additional water investment.
    Research advancements make it possible to use different types of water including produced water from other wells, saline groundwater, or even wastewater from other industries, cities, and households (“grey water”).

    5 of 6

    5 of 6

    .

    How has fracking affected U.S. CO2 emissions in the past decade?

    They’re up
    No impact
    They're down

    5 of 6

    That's correct!

    That's incorrect!

    America is the world’s No. 1 producer of natural gas, which has become the leading fuel source for generating electricity. Increased natural gas use is the main reason U.S. carbon emissions have fallen.

    Next

    Hotspot
    In the last 20 years, the industry has been able to reduce emissions while the economy has grown 60% and energy consumption has grown 14%.
    Hotspot
    In 2015, energy-related carbon dioxide emissions were 12% below 2005 levels, mostly because of changes in the electric power sector.
    In the last 20 years, the industry has been able to reduce emissions while the economy has grown 60% and energy consumption has grown 14%.
    In 2015, energy-related carbon dioxide emissions were 12% below 2005 levels, mostly because of changes in the electric power sector.

    6 of 6

    6 of 6

    .

    Is it common that the materials used during the fracking process enter the water supply?

    Yes
    No

    6 of 6

    That's correct!

    That's incorrect!

    It's extremely unlikely. A U.S. Environmental Protection Agency draft assessment report found fracking has not led to “widespread systemic impacts on drinking water resources in the United States.”

    Hotspot

    Hotspot
    A typical natural gas well uses 3 million pounds of steel and cement. Each layer of steel casing is cemented in place to create an air-tight seal.
    Monitoring technology is used to ensure integrity is maintained and the natural environment is protected.
